   <titles>
      <title>New Sequences from Old</title>
      <plain.title>New Sequences from Old</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we describe several ways of building a new sequences from one or several given ones: the product of a sequence bby a number, the sum of two sequences, the product of two sequences, a subsequence of a sequence, and a rearrangement of a sequence.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_SumProductSequences">
               <caption>Sum and product of sequences</caption>
               <associate type="Example">
                  <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_SequenceSumProduct"/>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Some examples of sums and products of sequences</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>Given sequences <math>
                           <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>(b_n)</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>\RNr</latex>
                        </math>,</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <ul>
                     <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>their sum is <math>
                                 <latex>(a_n) + (b_n) := (a_n + b_n)</latex>
                              </math>;
					</para.body>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>sum</term>
                              <term>of two sequences</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                     </li>
                     <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>their product is <math>
                                 <latex>(a_n) \cdot (b_n) := (a_n \cdot b_n)</latex>
                              </math>;
					</para.body>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>product</term>
                              <term>of two sequences</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                     </li>
                     <li>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>the product of <math>
                                 <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                              </math> by <math>
                                 <latex>t\in \RNr</latex>
                              </math> is <math>
                                 <latex>t\cdot(a_n) := (t\cdot a_n)</latex>
                              </math>.
					</para.body>
                           <index.glossary>
                              <term>product</term>
                              <term>of a sequence by a number</term>
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </index.glossary>
                        </para>
                     </li>
                  </ul>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_SubSequence">
               <caption>Subsequence</caption>
               <associate type="Illustration">
                  <unit.ref unitId="Illu_SubSequence"/>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>An illustration of the concept of subsequence.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <associate type="Example">
                  <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_SubSequence"/>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>A set of worked examples on subsequences.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A subsequence of a sequence <math>
                           <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                        </math> is given by a composite
				</para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>subsequence</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>\NNr \overset{n}{\longrightarrow} \NNr \overset{a}{\longrightarrow} \RNr</latex>
                  </math.display>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>where <math>
                           <latex>n</latex>
                        </math> is a strictly increasing function. We write <math>
                           <latex>(a_{n_i})</latex>
                        </math> for the resulting subsequence of <math>
                           <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                        </math>.
				</para.body>
                     <index.symbol>
                        <symbol>
                           <math>
                              <latex>a_{n_i}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </symbol>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Subsequence of the sequence <math>
                                    <latex>a_n</latex>
                                 </math>.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.symbol>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>To prepare for the study of limits of sequences, we introduce the following special kind of subsequence.</para.body>
            </para>
            <def type="Terminology" id="Def_TailEnd">
               <caption>Tail (end) of a sequence</caption>
               <associate type="Example">
                  <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_SequenceTail"/>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Example</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>A tail end of <math>
                              <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                           </math> results from omitting an initial segment</para.body>
                     </para>
                     <math.display>
                        <latex>a_0,\ a_1,\ a_2,\ \dots\ ,a_{N-1}</latex>
                     </math.display>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>from the original sequence. – Worked examples are available here.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A tail (end) of a sequence <math>
                           <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                        </math> is a subsequence of the form</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>(a_{n_i} = a_{N+i})</latex>
                  </math.display>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>for some <math>
                           <latex>N\in \NNr</latex>
                        </math>.
				</para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>tail end</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>A special kind of subsequence. – Definition of the concept.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>sequence</term>
                        <term>tail (end)</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>A special kind of subsequence. – Definition of the concept.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>For future reference we include here the less frequently used concept of rearrangement of a sequence.</para.body>
            </para>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_SequenceRearrangement">
               <caption>Rearrangement of a sequence</caption>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A rearrangement of a sequence <math>
                           <latex>(a_n)</latex>
                        </math> is given by a composite</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>\NNr \overset{n}{\longrightarrow} \NNr \overset{a}{\longrightarrow} \RNr</latex>
                  </math.display>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>in which the function <math>
                           <latex>n\from \NNr\to \NNr</latex>
                        </math> is invertible.
				</para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>rearrangement</term>
                        <term>of a sequence</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>sequence</term>
                        <term>rearrangement</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Definition of the concept</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
         </block.body>
      </block>
